label.value: abolished equatorial endocytosis during mitosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which endocytosis does not occur in the equatorial region of the cell during mitosis as in wild-type cells.

label.value: decreased microtubule binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of a protein to one or more microtubules occurs to a lower extent than normal. The affected protein may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with actin filaments that is affected by a mutation, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished microtubule bundle formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule bundle formation, which normally results in a parallel arrangement of microtubules, does not occur.

label.value: protein mislocalized to plasma membrane during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a protein that is not normally found at the plasma membrane is observed there.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used to annotate any case where a protein is found in the medial cortex in a mutant, but not in wild type. In some cases, there may be enough additional information to annotate to 'abnormal protein localization' (FYPO:0000443) or one of its descendants. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased duration of protein phosphorylation during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the duration of protein phosphorylation is longer than normal the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. All phosphorylation may be affected, or only phosphorylation of specific proteins, or even specific sites within specific proteins.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: bipolar mitotic spindle with decreased, irregular thickness

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the mitotic spindle has two poles and can elongate during anaphase, but has decreased and non-uniform thickness along its length.

definition.value: In images of thin spindles, polar microtubules may appear not to reach continuously from pole to pole.

label.value: sensitive to mechlorethamine

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to mechlorethamine. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of mechlorethamine that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal growth on mechlorethamine

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing mechlorethamine.

label.value: abolished protein localization to chromatin at promoter

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at one or more specific promoter elements is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: mitotic spindle microtubules detached from spindle pole body

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic spindle microtubules become disconnected from the spindle pole body.

label.value: normal F-actin level in actomyosin contractile ring during early mitosis

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of filamentous actin (F-actin) in the actomyosin contractile ring is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during early mitosis (before anaphase).

label.value: increased centromere central core transcript level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which RNAs transcribed from the centromere central core are present at greater levels than normal. Normally, the central core is not transcribed.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal transcription during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which transcription is abnormal when the cell is subject to glucose starvation. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be affected.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: delayed onset of transcription during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which transcription begins later than normal when the cell is subject to glucose starvation. All genes, or a specific subset of genes, may be affected.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: abnormal chromatin remodeling

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which chromatin remodeling, i.e. any dynamic structural change to chromatin, is abnormal.

label.value: decreased chromatin remodeling during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which chromatin remodeling, i.e. any dynamic structural change to chromatin, occurs to a lower extent than normal when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: abolished chromatin remodeling during glucose starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which chromatin remodeling, i.e. any dynamic structural change to chromatin, does not occur when the cell is subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

label.value: decreased protein exchange at pericentric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the movement of a protein in cis and trans between heterochromatin domains occurs to a lower extent than normal in regions of pericentric heterochromatin.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein exchange at pericentric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the movement of a protein in cis and trans between heterochromatin domains occurs to a greater extent than normal in regions of pericentric heterochromatin.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 dimethylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased borderline-derived siRNA level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which small interfering RNA transcripts derived from the lncRNA borderline are present at lower levels than normal.

label.value: monopolar spindle during meiosis I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the spindle forms with microtubules emanating from only one pole during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal spindle organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal spindle morphology.

label.value: spindle microtubules detached from spindle pole body during meiosis I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which meiotic spindle microtubules become disconnected from the spindle pole body during the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: meiotic spindle pole body detached from nucleus

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the meiotic spindle pole body (SPB) dissociates from the nucleus. Normally the SPB is embedded in the nuclear envelope.

label.value: abolished meiotic telomere clustering

value.value: A meiosis phenotype in which meiotic telomere clustering does not occur. Meiotic telomere clustering is the dynamic reorganization of telomeres in early meiotic prophase, during which meiotic chromosome ends are gathered in a bouquet arrangement at the inner surface of the nuclear envelope proximal to the spindle pole body.

label.value: normal spatial extent of centromeric heterochromatin assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin is assembled over a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) portion of the centromeric region of the chromosome.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 dimethylation at heterochromatin domain during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in one or more heterochromatin domains occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased protein exchange at subtelomeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the movement of a protein in cis and trans between heterochromatin domains occurs to a lower extent than normal in regions of subtelomeric heterochromatin.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal duration of meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: incomplete meiotic chromosome segregation, with chromosomal bridge

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids do not separate completely during meiosis I or meiosis II, and partially separated DNA masses are connected by one or more bridges formed of chromatin.

definition.value: Chromosome lagging may reflect a delay in detachment of homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids from each other ('chromosome separation' as defined by GO:0051307), polewards movement (GO:0016344), or both.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 dimethylation at heterochromatin island during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in one or more heterochromatin islands occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: abnormal protein processing

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which protein processing is abnormal. Protein processing is the cleavage of one or more bonds within a protein that leads to the formation of mature, fully functional protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein processing during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the protein processing does not occur when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. Processing of all proteins or of one or more specific proteins may be affected. Protein processing is any protein maturation process achieved by the cleavage of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein processing during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular metabolism phenotype in which the observed occurrence of protein processing is decreased when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the endoplasmic reticulum is abnormal.

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found in the ER and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the endoplasmic reticulum is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: Encompasses both presence of proteins not normally found in the ER and decreased levels or absence of proteins normally found there, and describes defects in a localization process. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to endoplasmic reticulum during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus does not occur when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to vacuole during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the vacuole is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased cellular reactive oxygen species level during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of reactive oxygen species (ROS) measured in a cell is higher than normal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

label.value: abnormal cell wall organization during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cell wall organization is abnormal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. Cell wall organization results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the fungal-type cell wall.

label.value: abnormal sporulation resulting in formation of ascus containing non-uniform spores and unencapsulated DNA

value.value: A sporulation phenotype that results in the formation of an ascus that contains spores of non-uniform size and DNA content, as well as DNA that is not contained within any of the spores. There may also be fewer than four spores.

label.value: decreased rate of endocytosis during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of endocytosis is decreased when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation. A phenotype may affect endocytosis of all cargoes, or of specific cargo such as a particular protein.

label.value: normal protein localization to cell tip during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell tip is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: protein abnormally dispersed at shmoo tip

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein that normally localizes to a compact region at the tip of a shmoo, or mating projection, is more dispersed than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal mitotic spindle pole body organization

value.value: A cell phenotype in which mitotic spindle pole body organization is abnormal. Mitotic spindle pole body organization is a process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the mitotic spindle pole body (SPB).

label.value: abnormal meiotic spindle pole body organization during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which meiotic spindle pole body organization is abnormal during the first meiotic nuclear division. Meiotic spindle pole body organization is a process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the meiotic spindle pole body (SPB).

label.value: normal meiotic spindle pole body oscillation during prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the meiotic spindle pole body (SPB) moves rapidly back and forth within the nuclear envelope to a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) extent during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: multiple meiotic spindles

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which a cell contains more than one meiotic spindle during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

label.value: meiotic spindle absent from cell during meiosis

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the cell does not contain a detectable meiotic spindle during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

label.value: abolished protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle pole body is abolished during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.
